name: Bacon
description: Generally served hot, and often eaten with ketchup or brown sauce

name: Bacon, egg and cheese
description: A breakfast sandwich, usually with fried or scrambled eggs

name: Baked bean
description: Canned baked beans on white or brown bread, sometimes with butter.

name: Bánh mì[4]
description: Filling is typically meat, but can contain a wide range of foods, including sardines, tofu, pâté, or eggs. Served on an airy baguette with pickled carrots, cilantro and peppers.

name: Barbecue[5][6][7]
description: Served on a bun, with chopped or sliced meat (pulled pork, beef, or chicken typically), and sometimes topped with coleslaw

name: Barros Jarpa
description: Ham and cheese, usually mantecoso, which is similar to farmer cheese

name: Barros Luco
description: Beef (usually thin-cut steak) and cheese

name: Bauru
description: Melted cheese, roast beef, tomato, and pickled cucumber in a hollowed-out French roll

name: Beef on weck
description: Roast beef on a Kummelweck Roll

name: BLT
description: Named for its ingredients: bacon, lettuce, and tomato. Often served on toasted sliced bread spread with mayonnaise.

name: Bologna sandwich
description: Pre-sliced and sometimes fried bologna sausage between slices of white bread, with various condiments such as ketchup, mustard, and mayonnaise.

name: Bosna
description: Usually grilled on white bread, containing a bratwurst sausage, onions, and a blend of tomato ketchup, mustard, and curry powder

name: Breakfast roll
description: A convenience dish on a variety of bread rolls, containing such breakfast items as sausages, bacon, white or black pudding, mushrooms, tomatoes, hash browns, and fried eggs, often eaten with ketchup or brown sauce

name: Breakfast
description: Typically a scrambled or fried egg, cheese, and a sausage patty or other breakfast meat, served on a biscuit or English muffin

name: British Rail
description: A dated reference to the poor quality of catering on the now-defunct British Rail, this refers to any poor-quality sandwich, often stale.

name: Broodje kroket
description: A soft bread roll containing a ragout-based croquette, often eaten with mustard.

name: Bun kebab
description: Consists of a shallow-fried, spicy patty, onions, and chutney or raita in a hamburger or hot dog bun.

name: Butterbrot
description: Single, open-faced, containing butter as the common ingredient, with sweet or savory toppings depending on the meal

name: Cemita
description: Sliced avocado, meat, white cheese, onions, and red sauce (salsa roja), on a fluffy sesame-seeded egg roll, originally from the city of Puebla.

name: Chacarero
description: Thinly sliced churrasco-style steak, or lomito-style pork, with tomatoes, green beans, and green chiles, served on a round roll

name: Cheese
description: In the United States this is usually made with American cheese, and often served toasted alongside tomato soup or with sliced tomato inside. When toasted (pictured), it is commonly referred to as a "grilled cheese sandwich."

name: Cheese and pickle
description: Slices of cheese (typically Cheddar) and pickle (a sweet, vinegary chutney with the most popular brand being Branston), sandwiched between two slices of bread.

name: Cheesesteak
description: Thinly sliced steak and melted cheese in a long roll, also known as a Philadelphia or Philly cheesesteak.

name: Chicken
description: Claimed to be created by Chick-Fil-A in their slogan, "WE DIDN'T INVENT THE CHICKEN, JUST THE CHICKEN SANDWICH."[8]Commonly referred to as a "Chick-Fil-A Sandwich," it consists of a crispy fried chicken breast fillet and two dill pickle chips on a round white bun that is sliced in half, buttered and grilled on a flat top. It is usually served without the addition of condiments. This type of sandwich is also often referred to as a "southern-style chicken sandwich" when discussed in general.

name: Chicken salad
description: A sandwich prepared with chicken salad as a filling.

name: Chickpea salad[9][10]
description: Chickpea salad is a vegan sandwich filling with a texture similar to tuna salad. Chickpea salad consists of mashed up chickpeas, vegenaise, onions, and other seasonings. Some versions also include tuna.[11]

name: Chili burger
description: A hamburger, with the patty topped with chili con carne

name: Chip butty[12][13][14][15]
description: Sliced white bread (or a large, flat bread roll) filled with chips, usually sprinkled with salt and vinegar or tomato ketchup.

name: Chipped beef
description: A sandwich prepared with thinly sliced or pressed salted and dried beef. Some chipped beef is smoked to add flavor.

name: Chivito
description: Filet mignon with mozzarella, tomatoes, mayonnaise, and commonly bacon, black or green olives, fried or hardboiled eggs, and ham

name: Choripán
description: Grilled chorizo, usually served on a crusty roll with salsa-type condiments, such as pebre, salsa criolla, or chimichurri. Morcipán is a variety of this using black pudding or blood sausage.

name: Chow mein
description: A brown gravy base and chow mein mixture on a hamburger-style bun

name: Churrasco
description: Thinly cut steak, grilled and served on a toasted bun. It can be served with almost any other ingredient, in which case its name changes to "churrasco+the new ingredient" (e.g.: churrasco palta = churrasco and avocado)

name: Club
description: A triple-decker sandwich made with sliced turkey or chicken, bacon, tomato, and lettuce; usually contains mayonnaise

name: Corned beef
description: Corned beef with mustard, usually on rye bread

name: Crisp
description: Crisps and occasionally pickles on white bread

name: Croque-monsieur
description: A grilled ham and cheese (typically Emmental or Gruyère) sandwich, sometimes coated in a mornay or béchamel sauce

name: Croque-madame
description: Same as a croque-monsieur, but with a fried egg on top.

name: Cuban
description: Ham, roasted pork, Swiss cheese, pickles, mustard, and sometimes Genoa salami on Cuban bread, usually pressed and warmed in a plancha

name: Cucumber
description: Two thin slices of crustless, lightly buttered white bread, containing paper-thin slices of peeled cucumber

name: Cudighi
description: Spicy cudighi (a Michigan variety of Cotechino Italian sausage), on a long, hard roll, often topped with mozzarella and tomato sauce

name: Dagwood
description: Multiple layers containing a wide variety of meats and condiments, named for Dagwood Bumstead of the comic strip Blondie

name: Deli sandwich
description: This sandwich may be ordered at a deli; choices include type of bread (toasted or untoasted,) type of meat (cold cut), type of sliced cheese, vegetable fillings (lettuce, tomato, onion, etc.), and condiments

name: Denver
description: A sandwich containing a Denver omelette

name: Doner kebab
description: Doner kebab is meat cooked on a vertical spit, normally veal or beef but also may be a mixture of these with lamb, and sometimes chicken. This may be served wrapped in a flatbread such as lavash or pita, or as a sandwich.

name: Donkey burger
description: Chopped or shredded savory donkey meat in a bun, sold in Baoding, Hebei Province as street food, and also in high-end restaurants

name: Double Down
description: This sandwich, created by KFC, consists of "bacon, two different kinds of melted cheese, the Colonel’s secret sauce... pinched in between two pieces of Original Recipe [fried] chicken fillets."[17]

name: Doubles
description: Two flat fried bara (bread), containing curried chickpeas or garbanzo beans

name: Dynamite
description: Made of ground beef, tomato sauces, spices and many onions and peppers. It is a popular food served at local family gatherings and fundraising benefits, usually made in large quantities.

name: Dyrlægens natmad
description: On a piece of dark rye bread, a layer of leverpostej, topped with a slice of salt beef and a slice of meat aspic, topped with raw onion rings and garden cress.

name: Elvis sandwich
description: Peanut butter, banana, and bacon

name: Egg
description:
Generic sandwich: This contains eggs, usually sliced hard boiled eggs or egg salad, but may be made with fried or (more rarely) scrambled egg, topped with the local roe spread, locally called kaviar.
Egg salad sandwich: A chopped egg mixed with mayonnaise.
Eggs Benedict is an open-faced sandwich consisting of an English muffin topped with meat, eggs, and hollandaise sauce.

name: Fairy bread
description: White bread with nonpareils (= 'sprinkles' (U.S.) or 'hundreds and thousands' (U.K.)) on a spread of butter. Often cut into squares or triangles.

name: Falafel
description: Deep-fried balls of ground, seasoned chickpeas topped with salad vegetables, hot sauce, tahini-based sauces, and pickled vegetables, wrapped in or added to the pocket of a split-open pita bread.

name: Fischbrötchen
description: Crusty bread rolls filled with fish (most commonly Bismarck or soused herring) and onions

name: Fool's Gold Loaf
description: Consists of a single warmed, hollowed-out loaf of bread filled with one jar of creamy peanut butter, one jar of grape jelly, and a pound of bacon. In 1976, Elvis Presley and some of his friends flew to Colorado to consume them.[18]

name: Fluffernutter
description: Peanut butter and marshmallow creme. Pictured is a fluffernutter sandwich prior to being assembled.

name: Francesinha
description: Wet-cured ham, linguiça, fresh sausage (chipolata), steak or other roast meat, topped with melted cheese, a hot thick tomato, and beer sauce

name: Francesinha poveira
description: A bun with wet-cured ham, linguiça, and cheese, sauced with butter or margarine, piri-piri, and port wine, whiskey, cognac, or brandy

name: French dip
description: Thinly sliced roast beef on a baguette, served hot, usually au jus (with juice)

name: Fried brain
description: Sliced calves' brain on sliced bread

name: Fruit
description: Fruit, often fruits such as banana, fig or pineapple served on bread, often with mayonnaise in the United States.

name: Ftira[19][20]
description: A traditional Maltese sandwich[21] made on a large round piece of Maltese ftira bread, topped with tomato paste, tuna, capers, and red onions.

name: Gatsby
description: A deli-style sandwich similar to the hoagie, often containing french fries, with other variations, prepared with masala steak, chicken, polony, Vienna sausages, calamari, fish, or chargrilled steak

name: Gerber
description: Half section of Italian or French bread with garlic butter, containing ham, provel or provolone cheese, topped with paprika, then toasted

name: Guajolota
description: A tamale inserted in a Mexican bread, bolillo, easy to find in Mexico City streets in the morning, also called torta de tamal

name: Gyro
description: "Pita gyro" or "psomaki gyro," depending on the type of bread used, includes meat roasted on a vertical spit, with tomato, potatoes, raw, often red onion and tzatziki sauce, wrapped in pita or sandwich bread.

name: Hagelslag or vlokken
description: Chocolate sprinkles or flakes usually served on buttered bread

name: Ham
description: Ham, often with mustard

name: Ham and cheese
description: A common sandwich prepared with ham and sliced cheese. Additional ingredients may include lettuce, tomato, mayonnaise, and other ingredients.

name: Ham and egg bun
description: Sliced Danish canned ham with sliced scrambled egg sheet in a halved sweet bun

name: Hamburger
description: A ground beef patty, often with vegetables, sauces and other meats, usually on a round bun.

name: Hamdog
description: A hot dog wrapped in a beef patty, deep-fried, then covered with chili, a few french fries, and a fried egg

name: Horseshoe
description: A thick-sliced, toasted, open-faced sandwich, it usually contains hamburger patties or ham, but other meat, such as deep-fried pork tenderloin, grilled or fried chicken breast, and fried fish filets, can be used. The meat is topped with french fries and covered with a cheese sauce.

name: Hot brown
description: Open-faced with turkey and bacon, topped with mornay sauce, and baked or broiled

name: Hot dog
description: A sausage or cylindrical processed meat, placed in a bun, often topped with ketchup, mustard, relish and onions. Many regional varieties in the United States.

name: Hot chicken
description: Coarsely shredded or sliced chicken, sandwiched between two pieces of sliced bread, and completely covered with gravy.

name: Hot turkey[23][24][25]
description: Often open-faced, sliced turkey on white bread drenched in turkey gravy, often served with mashed potatoes. These are sometimes served at Hofbrau-style restaurants.

name: Ice cream
description: Vanilla ice cream between thin biscuits, cookies or slices of cake, normally chocolate

name: Italian beef
description: Thin slices of seasoned, juicy roast beef, often garnished with giardiniera or Italian sweet peppers, on a dense, long Italian-style roll

name: Italiano[26]
description: Not a sandwich, it refers to a set of toppings to put in a sandwich, refers to the colors of the Italian flag: red (tomato), white (mayonnaise) and green (avocado)

name: Jam
description: Buttered bread, with jam (traditionally strawberry), normally eaten at lunchtime or as a quick snack, may also be eaten at breakfast or for high tea

name: Jambon-beurre
description: A French baguette with butter and ham. Also known as "Parisien," it is the most popular sandwich in France.

name: Jibarito
description: Meat, cheese, lettuce, and tomato, between flattened, fried green plantains (instead of bread), with garlic-flavored mayonnaise

name: Jucy Lucy
description: A cheeseburger with the cheese inside the meat patty rather than on top

name: Katsu sando
description: Breaded, deep-fried pork cutlet (tonkatsu)

name: Kokoretsi
description: Lamb or goat intestines, containing seasoned offal

name: Kottenbutter
description: Buttered brown bread with smoked pork sausage (Kottenwurst), fresh onion rings, and spicy mustard

name: Leberkäse
description: A meatloaf-like dish which, despite the name, contains neither liver nor cheese. It is commonly served on a Kaiser roll with mustard.

name: Lettuce
description: Lettuce and mayonnaise

name: Limburger sandwich
description: They are typically prepared with buttered rye bread, Limburger cheese, sliced onion and mustard. Pictured is Limburger cheese and bread.

name: Lobster roll
description: Lobster meat tossed with either mayonnaise ("cold") or drawn butter ("hot") stuffed into a slit opening at the top of a grilled bread roll or hot dog bun.

name: Lox
description: Lox on a bagel with cream cheese, thinly sliced onion, capers, and sometimes sliced tomato

name: Luther burger
description: A hamburger or cheeseburger on glazed doughnuts instead of a bun

name: Marmite
description: Marmite spread thinly with butter or margarine onto toast or bread

name: Martino[27]
description: Filet américain (steak tartare) with Worcestershire sauce, pickles, onions, peppers, and martino sauce

name: Meatball
description: Meatballs in marinara sauce, with melted Parmesan or provolone cheese, on a long bun or section of Italian loaf. Might include Italian-style accompaniments such as bell peppers, basil, or Italian-dressed lettuce

name: Medianoche
description: Roast pork, ham, mustard, Swiss cheese, and dill pickles served on sweet bread.

name: Mitraillette
description: French fries and fried meat with sauce on a demi-baguette.

name: Melt
description: A generic sandwich containing a filling and a layer of cheese, grilled or fried until the cheese is melted

name: Mettbrötchen
description: Open sandwich consisting of a sliced bun, topped with Mett (seasoned minced pork without bacon), frequently with a garnish of raw onion rings or diced raw onion

name: Mollete
description: A typical food of Mexico and a kind of bread in Spain. In Mexico, Molletes are prepared with melted cheese and beans with other ingredients, such as salsa, ham, or bacon.

name: Montadito[28][29]
description: Small, usually grilled, and may contain a variety of fillings. Some bars offer a variety of 200 different types of these sandwiches.[citation needed]

name: Monte Cristo
description: Sliced ham and cheese (usually Emmental or Gruyère) between slices of French toast and batter-fried. In some regions it is sprinkled with powdered sugar and served with jelly or jam). In other regions (New England), it is served savory with French mustard and no powdered sugar.

name: Montreal-style smoked meat
description: A sandwich made from cured and smoked brisket with yellow mustard, usually on rye bread.

name: Mortadella
description: Any sandwich containing mortadella, a large Italian sausage

name: Mother-in-law
description: A hot dog bun containing a Chicago-style corn-roll tamale, topped with chili

name: Muffuletta
description: Originated in New Orleans' Italian-American community, this contains meats, cheeses, and olive salad on a round bun

name: Naan sandwich
description: Hamburger on naan bread. Sometimes ham is used instead of beef.

name: Open-faced sandwich[30][31]
description: Consists of a single slice of bread with one or more food items on top. See also pizza.

name: Pambazo
description: Made with pambazo bread dipped in a red guajillo pepper sauce and filled with potatoes and chorizo.

name: Pan-bagnat
description: Round bread (bread bagnats) topped with green salad, tomatoes, hard-boiled eggs, tuna, anchovies, cucumbers, fava beans, artichokes, green peppers, radishes, onions, basil, and black olives. Condiments may include garlic, vinegar, olive oil, salt, and pepper. Served chilled.

name: Panini
description: In Italy, panino is the word for a sandwich made from bread other than sliced bread, in which case Italians call it a tramezzino. Examples of bread types used are ciabatta, rosetta and baguette. The bread is cut horizontally and filled with deli ingredients such as salami, ham, cheese, mortadella, or other food, and is sometimes pressed by a warming grill. In the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada, the term panini is used to refer to a long pressed and toasted sandwich; there is widespread availability and use of sandwich presses, often known as "panini presses".

name: Patty melt
description: Consists of a hamburger patty, pieces of sautéed or grilled onion, and Cheddar or Swiss cheese between two slices of bread

name: Peanut butter and jelly
description: Jam is often used in place of jelly. Also known as a PB&J.

name: Pebete
description: A simple Argentine sandwich, traditionally filled with cheese, cured meat, tomato, and mayonnaise. Pebete actually refers to the bread used for the sandwich - a soft oval bun with a spongy inside, and a thin toasted crust.

name: Pistolette
description: A stuffed and fried bread roll (sometimes called stuffed pistolettes) in the Cajun areas around Lafayette. This also refers to a type of submarine-shaped bread about half the size of a baguette that is popular in New Orleans for Vietnamese bánh mì and other sandwiches.[32]

name: Pljeskavica
description: A patty dish popular in the Balkan region of Southeastern Europe, a sandwich utilizes the Pljeskavica patty and bread.

name: Ploughman's lunch
description: A cold meal originating in the United Kingdom, commonly served in pubs. Its core components are (cheddar) cheese, ploughman's pickle, and bread.[33] It is traditionally eaten with beer.

name: Po' boy
description: A crusty bread loaf typically filled with fried seafood or roast beef.

name: Polish boy
description: Kielbasa sausage in a bun, covered with french fries, barbecue sauce (or hot sauce), and coleslaw

name: Porilainen
description: A half-inch slice of thick sausage, usually with diced red or sweet onion, sliced pickles, ketchup, mustard, and sometimes mayonnaise, on white bread

name: Pork chop bun
description: A popular dish in Macau, the bun is extremely crisp outside and very soft inside, containing a freshly fried pork chop.

name: Pork tenderloin
description: A thin, tenderized, deep-fried pork loin, served on a bun.

name: Prawn roll
description: A thin, tenderized, deep-fried pork loin, served on a bun.

name: Primanti
description: Selection of grilled meats topped with french fries, coleslaw, and tomato on Italian bread

name: Prosperity Sandwich
description: Ham and turkey topped with broiled cheese. Sometimes includes bacon and tomato.

name: Pudgy Pie[34]
description: This sandwich can be made in a pan. Margarine on the outside, pizza sauce and fillings on the inside. The term "pudgy pie" is sometimes used to refer to pie irons, a gadget used for campfire cooking.[35][36]

name: Pulled pork sandwich
description: Form of barbecue in which pork is cooked using a slow cook method until the meat becomes tender enough that it can be "pulled", or easily broken into individual pieces. The pork is often topped with barbecue sauce and vinegar- or mayonnaise-based coleslaw depending on the region

name: Reuben
description: Corned beef, sauerkraut, Swiss cheese, topped with Russian or Thousand Island dressing, on rye bread, then grilled

name: Roti john
description: Basic ingredients are eggs, chopped onions, sambal paste, salt, and pepper, cooked as an omelette with the bread added on top before it's fully cooked. Many variations include canned sardines, chicken, beef, or mutton. Garnished with mayo, chili sauce, and cheese.

name: Rou jia mo
description: Stewed pork, chopped finely, and stuffed in mo, a kind of flatbread

name: Runza
description: A bun filled with a mixture of (usually) loose meat, cabbage, and cheese. The fillings are baked inside the bread, similar to a kolache. Popular in the Midwestern United States, especially Nebraska.

name: Sandwich loaf
description: Alternating layers of bread and filling frosted to resemble a layer cake

name: De miga
description: Made with single-, double-, or triple-layered, buttered, thin white bread with crust removed, toasted or untoasted, containing thinly sliced meat, as well as eggs, cheese, tomatoes, green peppers, lettuce, olives, and sometimes other vegetables.

name: Salt beef bagel
description: Especially noted from Beigel Bake in Brick Lane, east London.

name: Sausage
description: A sausage on a roll or bread, served with a variety of sauces and toppings.

name: Shawarma
description: Flatbread with fillings of beef, spinach, tomatoes, cucumber, and tahini sauce, wrapped and grilled.

name: Shuco
description: A dry hot dog bun containing guacamole, sliced cabbage, ketchup, mustard and mayonnaise. It's usually served with a sausage, but it can also be ordered with churrasco or adobado beef. Chopped onions and a variety of hot sauces are also available for the sandwich.

name: Slider
description: Essentially a miniature hamburger about three inches in diameter, but may also contain other ingredients

name: Sloppy joe
description: Ground meat, usually beef, cooked with seasoned tomato sauce and served on a round bun.

name: Sloppy joe (New Jersey)
description: A triple decker rye bread sandwich made with one or more types of sliced deli meat, such as turkey, ham, pastrami, corned beef, roast beef, or sliced beef tongue, along with Swiss cheese, coleslaw, and Russian dressing

name: Smörgåstårta
description: Multiple layers of white or light rye bread containing creamy fillings, such as egg and mayonnaise, liver paté, olives, shrimp, ham, various cold cuts, caviar, tomato, cucumber, cheese, and smoked salmon

name: Smørrebrød
description: Open-faced, buttered dark rye bread with cold cuts, pieces of meat or fish, cheese, or spreads

name: Sol over Gudhjem
description: An open-faced sandwich on rugbrød, with smoked herring, chives, and a raw egg yolk

name: Souvlaki
description: A sizzling skewer of lamb, beef, pork, or chicken roasted, shaved off the spit, and marinade ranging from hot barbecue to sweet, all laid out on a rolled pita bread, sprinkled with your choice of lettuce, tomato, cheese, red onion, and oregano, and doused with tzatziki sauce.

name: Spiedie
description: Marinated cubes of chicken, pork, lamb, veal, venison, or beef, grilled on a spit, and served in a bun

name: St. Paul
description: An egg foo young patty (containing bean sprouts and minced white onions), dill pickle slices, white onion, mayonnaise, lettuce, and tomato on white bread

name: Steak bomb
description: A grilled, over-stuffed submarine roll, containing shaved steak, and topped with salami, melted provolone, sautéed onions, and bell peppers.

name: Steak burger
description: Typically prepared with ground, sliced or minced beefsteak meat. Additional meats are also used.

name: Steak
description: Prepared with cooked steak, served on bread or a roll. Steak sandwiches may include toppings such as cheese, onions, mushrooms, bell peppers, hot peppers, tomatoes, and in some instances fried eggs, cole slaw, or french fries.

name: Submarine/Sub/Baguette
description: A generic sandwich served on a long French or Italian roll which may contain a wide variety of sliced meats, vegetables, and condiments, including lettuce, tomato, sweet peppers, onions, olives, and mushrooms. Also known regionally as a hero, a hoagie, a grinder, or a zep, among other names. In the United Kingdom it is named a baguette, after the French bread used to make it.

name: Taco
description: A traditional Mexican sandwich composed of a corn or wheat tortilla folded or rolled around a filling

name: Tavern
description: Common in Iowa, consists of a mixture of unseasoned ground beef and sauteed onions, sometimes topped with pickles, ketchup, and mustard, on a bun

name: Tea
description: Thinly sliced white bread with crusts removed, lightly buttered, containing a light spread of cream cheese or mayonnaise mixture, and often radishes, cucumber, asparagus, or watercress. Other fillings may be pimento cheese, ham with mustard, smoked salmon, fruit jam, curried chicken, and egg salad.

name: The Scooch
description: Contains hot sopressata, capicola, and primadonna cheese, on a ciabatta roll, grilled, with balsamic vinegar, extra virgin olive oil, roasted red peppers, and sliced hot cherry peppers[37]

name: TLT (Tempeh, Lettuce, and Tomato)[38][39][40]
description: Vegan version of the BLT: smoky baked tempeh, lettuce, tomato, and avocado, served on toasted sourdough bread

name: Toast
description: A thin slice of toast between two thin slices of bread with a layer of butter, and salt and pepper to taste.

name: Toast Hawaii
description: A slice of toast with ham, a maraschino cherry in the middle of a pineapple slice, and cheese, grilled from above, so the cheese starts to melt.

name: Toastie
description: Two slices of bread with various fillings, toasted in a sandwich toaster.

name: Tofu Sandwich[41][42]
description: Tofu, typically broiled or baked, with vegetables.

name: Tongue toast
description: Sautéed beef tongue and scrambled eggs, served open-faced[43][44] ada pav

name: Torta
description: Round roll stuffed with sliced meat, sauce, and other ingredients, often made ahead and tightly wrapped to meld the filling with the bread.

name: Torta ahogada
description: Birote bread (bolillo) sliced open on one side, and filled with chopped, fried pork, and sometimes shredded chicken or other meat, beans and cheese, served submerged in a sauce made mostly of a dried chile de árbol.

name: Tramezzino
description: Triangular white bread with the crusts removed, with fillings such as tuna and olive and prosciutto, served in Italian bars throughout the day

name: Tripleta[45][46][47]
description: Although there are numerous variations, the main distinction is a combination of three meats, typically grilled, such as beef (usually churrasco steak or cube steak), roast pork (pernil), chicken, and ham. Condiments may include some combination of mustard, ketchup, and mayonnaise, often combined to create a “special” sauce. Popular toppings include thin crispy fried potato sticks or shoestring potatoes, thinly sliced cabbage, lettuce, onion, tomato, pickles, and Swiss cheese. The sandwich is often toasted in a sandwich press.

name: Tuna
description: Usually made with tuna salad and may include mayonnaise and celery. Other common variations include the tuna boat and tuna melt.

name: Vada pav
description: A potato fritter coated in chickpea flour (batata vada) in a bun[48]

name: Vegemite
description: Vegemite is a dark brown Australian food paste made from used brewers' yeast extract, a by-product of beer manufacturing, various vegetables, wheat, and spice additives. It is a spread for sandwiches, toast, crumpets, and cracker biscuits, as well as a filling for pastries.

name: Vegetable
description: Many types of vegetables are used to prepare vegetable sandwiches.

name: Welsh rarebit
description: A hot melted cheese sauce, poured over slices (or other pieces) of toasted bread. The hot cheese sauce may also be served in a bowl accompanied by the toast.

name: Wrap
description: Flat bread (often a tortilla) tightly wrapped around the sandwich filling with the ends tucked in to form a neat bundle. Fillings can vary widely.

name: Wurstbrot (sausage bread)
description: A simple and common German sandwich prepared with thin slices of lunch meat or sausage, sometimes buttered.

name: Yakisoba-pan
description: A hot dog bun stuffed with fried noodles, frequently topped with pickles, such as beni shōga, with mayonnaise

name: Zapiekanka
description: A halved baguette or other bread usually topped with mushrooms and cheese, ham or other meats, and vegetables
